    "summary": "Spot-checked 5 headline records via web search; all hard numbers verify. MV Prestige (243m/34.4m beam/18.7m depth/14m draft, 81,589 DWT, GT 42,820, Hitachi 1976) confirmed exactly against Wikipedia. Mozah Q-Max (345m/53m/12m draft, 266,000 m3, SHI 2008) confirmed exactly. Alaska-class (287.0m/50m beam, 185,286 DWT, NASSCO) confirmed. Almi VLCC IMO numbers (9583720/9583732=Almi Hydra/Hercules, 9816323/9816335=Almi Atlas/Titan) all resolve to real Almi/DSME & Hyundai Samho VLCCs; DWT 319,359 confirmed. All principal dimensions, displacements, Cb values are physically sane for each class (VLCC Cb~0.82, LNG~0.78, draft/beam/DWT ratios consistent; lightship+DWT sums to displacement correctly). No hard number is presented as fact without a citation: every derived value is explicitly prefixed 'estimated:' with stated derivation method, and unknowns are marked 'gap'. The IMDC 2024 TU Delft roll-period paper is a real, on-topic source for kxx (it uses a 0.40 roll coefficient; 0.33-0.40*B range is correct). Citations are solid. Minor (non-fabrication) caveats: (1) kyy/kzz pitch/yaw = 0.25*Lpp are generic rules of thumb attributed to a roll-only paper \u2014 scope overreach but values marked estimated; (2) several kyy estimates derive from LBP which is itself an estimated gap (derived-from-derived, but properly flagged); (3) the supplied DATA JSON is truncated mid-Mozah-record so the final citation URL could not be confirmed.",
